\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s23 \f3\fs20\cgrid \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard\plain \s23\fi-360\li648\ri288\keep\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls2\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls2\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {You can add multiple moving terrain objects to a single connected set of path waypoints.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s23 \f3\fs20\cgrid \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \s23\fi-360\li648\ri288\keep\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls2\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls2\adjustright {The MovingTerrain property automatically creates and destroys the physics property of the object.  OBB physics models are used for moving terrain, whose sizes are generated from the models' bounding boxes.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s23 \f3\fs20\cgrid \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \s23\fi-360\li648\ri288\keep\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls2\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls2\adjustright {Base friction can be specified on the moving terrain object to adjusting its cornering ability (when not path limited).  A value of 1.0 gives a fairly wide turning radius, whereas 6.0 appears almost path-limited.  3.0 is the default, and seems to be a happy medium.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s23 \f3\fs20\cgrid \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \s23\fi-360\li648\ri288\keep\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls2\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls2\adjustright {The MovingTerrain base script has OnMovingTerrainWaypoint() messages that indicate when an object has reached a waypoint.  See phmtscpt.h, and scripts/examples/mttest.scr.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s23 \f3\fs20\cgrid \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \s23\fi-360\li648\ri288\keep\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls2\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls2\adjustright {Moving terrain objects can be activated and deactivated by setting the MovingTerrain "active" property field.  This can be done on the fly.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s23 \f3\fs20\cgrid \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \s23\fi-360\li648\ri288\keep\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls2\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls2\adjustright {levels/misc/mtdemo.mis is a little level I did that has a bunch of moving terrain that you can play with. 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s23 \f3\fs20\cgrid \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \s23\fi-360\li648\ri288\keep\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls2\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls2\adjustright {"reset_moving_terrain" is the command to run to make sure all moving terrain is in the proper place, if you think something is out-of-sync.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s23 \f3\fs20\cgrid \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \s23\fi-360\li648\ri288\keep\nowidctlpar\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls2\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls2\adjustright {The code that handles steps does not currently work with OBB, so if you want to allow the player to step }{\i onto}{ an OBB, you need to make sure it is }{\i lower}{ than the terrain that the player is stepping from.
